   "lat": null,
   "lng": null,
   "narrative": "Joseph Lucian Bernard Gaudrault of Holyoke served as a Seaman First Class aboard the destroyer USS Shaw. On the morning of December 7, 1941, the Shaw lay in a floating drydock at Pearl Harbor when Japanese bombers struck her. Three bombs went through her, the fires reached her forward magazine, and she blew apart in an explosion so enormous that the photograph of it became the single most famous image of the attack — a fountain of fire and steel above the harbor. Gaudrault was killed in that blast. He was among the first Americans to die in the Second World War, in its opening hour, and among the first sons of Holyoke to fall. He was survived by his father, Mr. Arthur Gaudrault. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
