   "lat": null,
   "lng": null,
   "narrative": "Charles Verheyn of Holyoke entered the service in 1914, in the war's opening weeks, with the French Army — going to fight for France before most of the world understood what the war would become. He was wounded twice: bayoneted in the knee in a hand-to-hand encounter with the enemy, and disabled by shell shock, the injury that medicine of that day could neither name nor treat. He was invalided home in 1917, a Private who had given three years to a foreign army. He died in Holyoke on September 28, 1918, as a result of those injuries — in his own city, four years after he left it, killed by a war he had already come home from. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
