   "narrative": "Fay W. Williams entered Plattsburg in August 1917, trained at the Fortress Monroe Coast Artillery School, and received his commission as first lieutenant in November 1917. He went overseas with four hundred volunteer officers in December 1917, had charge of billeting the 51st and 56th Regiments, then volunteered for the air service and trained at the Aviation Instruction Centre at Tours. He went to the front in September 1918 as an aerial observer, took part in the drives at St. Mihiel, the Argonne Forest, and Sedan, and was in one of the first planes to cross into Luxembourg after the Armistice. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
